    I was born and raised in Yeongnam, and Mount Duryu is a mountain of my home region. Yet, wandering north and south in official service, lost in the dust of worldly affairs, I reached forty years of age without once setting foot upon it. In the spring of the year Sinmyo, when I became magistrate of Hamyang, the mountain lay within my jurisdiction—majestic and verdant, visible the moment one raised one's eyes. Yet calamity struck the harvest, the people's affairs pressed urgently upon me, and two years passed without my daring to make the ascent. Whenever I spoke of this with Yu Geuk-gi and Lim Jeong-suk, my heart was never free of regret.

    That summer, Cho Tae-heo came from the eastern provinces. We studied the Book of Rites together, and when autumn arrived, he wished to return to his family but first asked to see this mountain. I too felt my vigor waning with each passing day, my legs growing ever weaker. Should I fail to climb this year, next year would be uncertain. Moreover, it was mid-autumn—the damp haze had already cleared. On the night of the full moon, I could view the moon from Heaven King Peak; at cockcrow, watch the sun rise; and by bright morning, survey the four directions. Thus in one journey I would gain two rewards. We decided to go.

    I invited Geuk-gi and consulted with Tae-heo the provisions listed in the Book of Caring for Parents, adding and subtracting as needed. On the fourteenth day, the monk Haegong from Deokbong Temple came to serve as our guide, and Han Baek-won asked to join us. We passed through Eomcheon and rested at Hwaam.

    The monk Beopjong came following behind us. We questioned him about the paths he had traveled, and he gave detailed answers, so we had him guide us as well. At the fork toward Jijang Temple, we dismounted, put on straw sandals, and proceeded with walking sticks. The groves and valleys were clear and deep—I could already sense the mountain's sublime beauty. About a mile on, we came to a cliff called Welcome Terrace. Tae-heo and Baek-won climbed to its summit. Below it stretched a thousand feet, and we could see the Golden Temple, Red Lotus Hermitage, and White Lotus Hermitage far below.

    We sought out Former Nirvana Hermitage, built against towering cliffs. Two springs at the cliff's base were crystalline pure. Outside the walls, water from a cleft in the rock fell in streams onto flat stones, collecting in small clear pools where red willows and dragon-whisker grass grew several inches tall. Beside it ran a ladder path. A vine was tied to a tree for climbing up and down to travel between Wonderful Truth Hermitage and Earth Store Temple. Beopjong told us of a Buddhist monk who had settled here for summer retreat. After the Ghost Festival concluded, he had wandered away, leaving only small melons and radishes planted on the stones, with just a mortar and pestle and a few measures of grain.

    We sought New Nirvana Hermitage, also built against high cliffs. To its northeast stood towering stones called Solitary Woman Cliff—five separate peaks each over a thousand feet high. Beopjong said according to tradition, a woman once stacked stones here and dwelt alone, cultivating the Way until she ascended to the void. The stones she piled remain. Pine trees grow at the cliff's waist. To ascend, one must grasp the pine and climb around the rock, the entire back and front scraping against stone. Only those willing to risk life itself can reach the summit. Our attendant Okgun managed to climb and stand at the peak.

    I had often seen these cliffs from the mountain's shadow, how they rose like pillars supporting heaven. Now, standing at this very place, my hair stood on end. Was I truly myself? We continued westward to Ancient Nirvana Hermitage as the sun descended. The Discourse Terrace lay on the western slope. Geuk-gi lagged behind while I stood alone, leaning on my staff among three flat stones. Below me, the Incense Burner Peak and Amitabha Peak were as if beneath my feet.

    Haegong spoke of a stone cave below where an elder named Udara once dwelt, and how three monks had once sat upon this rock debating sudden enlightenment in both Mahayana and Hinayana—hence the name Discourse Terrace. Soon the lodge master, Monk Harupa, arrived with palms pressed together: "We hear the magistrate has come to visit. Where is he?" Haegong gestured for silence. The monk's face reddened. I comforted him with words from Zhuangzi: "Those wishing to warm themselves quarrel for the stove; those wishing to rest quarrel for the seat. Now the lodge master sees only an old villager. How could he know this man is a magistrate?" All laughed.

    That day I attempted steep climbing for nearly twenty miles and became utterly exhausted, sleeping deeply. At midnight I awoke to find moonlight swallowing and releasing the peaks while clouds rose and billowed. I sat in contemplation.

    At dawn on the next day, deeper shadow covered the sky. The lodge master said, "In my long residence here, I read the clouds. Today will surely bring no rain." Pleased, I sent the porters back and departed immediately. Through twisted green vines and thick bamboo groves, fallen trees lay across the stream paths, becoming natural bridges. We passed through several ridges—the first of the Nine Passes, Haegong announced.

    After traversing three or four more, we found a broad, deep cavern, its trees blocking sunlight, vines hanging everywhere, the stream murmuring with each bend. The eastern slope was not particularly steep; the western land descended gradually. After twenty miles, we reached Uitan Village. Had we brought chickens, cattle, and calves and cleared fields to plant grain, the Peach Blossom Spring itself could hardly compare. I struck a stream stone with my staff and turned to Geuk-gi: "Alas, could we not dwell in this place forever?" I had him scrape the moss from a rock and carve our names.

    After the nine passes, we followed the ridge where low clouds brushed our hats and the grass grew wet without rain. The sky seemed close. After a few miles heading south along the ridge, we reached Jinjuland. Mist and smoke obscured distant views. At Blue-Easing Hall—a wooden structure—the four of us rested on stream stones before it. The path from here to Younglang Pass was extremely treacherous, exactly as the Record of the Sealing Ceremony describes: "The rear sees only the front man's heels; the front sees only the rear man's brow." We grasped tree roots to ascend and descend.

    After midday we reached the pass. From Hamyang, this peak appeared highest. Here, Heaven King Peak towers above us. Younglang was leader of Silla's Flower Knights—he commanded three thousand disciples who wandered mountains and streams. He once climbed this peak, giving it his name. Youth Terrace stands at its side, a vast blue cliff thousands of feet high.

    I embraced a stone corner, peering downward as if about to fall, and warned my attendants not to come near. As the clouds and mist dispersed, sunlight descended. Eastern and western valleys opened wide. I saw no mixed forest—only fir, cypress, pine, and cedar, with one-third standing dead and skeletal. Maples appeared here and there like a painting. Ridge-top trees struggled against wind and fog, branches bent leftward and twisted, hair-like and windswept. Sea pines grew abundantly; locals gathered them each autumn to meet their tax quota. This year not a single tree bears fruit—if we force the quota, what becomes of my people? The magistrate witnessing this is fortunate. A grass resembling silk cord grew everywhere, soft and slippery enough to sit and sleep upon.

    Below Blue-Easing Hall grew many five-flavor berries, their dense forest giving way to none here—only Chinese spikenard and Chinese angelica. Passing Crab Ridge, a boat-shaped stone stood nearby. Beopjong said in ancient times when seas swept the land, a boat was moored here and crabs passed by—hence the name. I laughed: "By that logic, all creatures then clung to heaven itself!"

    We ascended Middle Peak together. Within the mountain, all that rises steeply is stone. This peak alone wears earth, dignified and suitable for military training. A spring below provided clear water. In drought, people climbing this rock and treading in a circle bring thunder and rain. I tested this last year and this summer—it works. In the afternoon we climbed Heaven King Peak.

    Clouds and mist crowded thick; the mountains darkened. Middle Peak disappeared from sight. Haegong and Beopjong went ahead to the Holy Mother Temple. They held a small Buddha, pleading for clear skies in jest. At first I thought them playful, but they said folk wisdom teaches this method works. I dressed properly, washed, and entered the temple. With wine and fruit, I made offering to the Holy Mother:

    "Your servant has long admired how Confucius climbed Mount Tai and how Han Yu traveled Mount Heng. Yet official duties bind me. This year in autumn, inspecting harvests in our southern border, I gazed upon this towering peak with utmost sincerity. With officers Han Inhyo, Yu Hoin, and Cao Wei, I ascended the cloud ladder to reach this sacred threshold. Yet the rain-spirit obscures things; clouds churn in confusion. In fear of wasting this perfect season, I humbly beseech the Holy Mother to accept this humble offering and grant her divine power. Let this evening's sky clear brilliantly and tomorrow morning shine ten thousand li bright, so that mountains and seas separate distinctly, granting us this sublime vista. We shall never forget such grace."

    After the ritual, we sat before the deity's altar, shared wine, and departed. The temple held but three rooms, built by Eomcheon villagers with boards nailed very firmly against the wind. Two monks decorated the walls. The so-called Holy Mother is a stone image, her face and hair painted with cosmetics. A crack mars her forehead. Asked about it, they said that when the Great Ancestor defeated enemies in the year Inyeol, Japanese pirates climbed the peak and struck it away. Later people glued it back together.

    A sunken stone cairn held the small Buddha the monks had toyed with—called the National Teacher, though folk legend claims he is the Holy Mother's lover. I asked: "What god is the Holy Mother?"

    "Maya, the Buddha's mother."

    Absurd! Western lands and eastern lands are separated by a hundred thousand worlds. How could an Indian woman become a deity of this land? I once read Li Seunghyu's Chronicle of Rulers. In his notation, it says "the Holy Mother's command to the monk Seon"—meaning the present Jiri Heaven King is actually the mother of Goryeo's Great Ancestor, Queen Wisuok. Goryeo people, hearing of celestial peach and Holy Mother legends, created this tale to sanctify their sovereign's line. Seunghyu believed it and recorded it. This too cannot be verified. How much less can we trust the raving nonsense of Buddhist monks! Moreover, having called her Maya, they blacken her name by calling her the National Teacher. Could disrespect be greater? This must be clarified.

    As darkness fell, fierce winds blew from all directions as if to tear the roof and shake the mountain. Clouds rushed in; our garments grew damp. All four of us lay in the temple, wracked by cold that pierced the bone. We added thick quilts; attendants trembled without composure. We lit three or four large logs to warm ourselves.

    Deep in the night, moonlight dimly shone. I rose to look but clouds quickly covered it. Leaning against the stone wall, surveying all directions, the six realms seemed formless as if we floated in a great ocean on a small boat, tilting this way and that, about to plunge into waves. I laughed and told my three companions: "Though we lack Han Yu's devotion and Zhi Wei's occult arts, fortunately dwelling together with you in this atmosphere, floating through primordial chaos—is this not sublime?"

    On the following day, wind and rain still raged. We sent attendants to Fragrant Accumulation Temple to prepare food and break trail for our return. After noon the rain lessened somewhat. With slippery stone paths, we helped each other down several miles until reaching an iron-chain route extremely perilous. We punched through stone passages instead, reaching Fragrant Accumulation Temple with great effort. No monk had dwelt here two years, yet water still flowed through split wood into a trough, windows remained latched, the incense stand and Buddha-oil remained. We swept clean, lit incense, and entered.

    At dusk, clouds rolled downward from Heaven King Peak so rapidly the eye could scarce blink. Distant reflected sunlight appeared. Delighted, I stepped onto a flat stone before the gate and gazed upon Salcheon winding its course, while mountains and island peaks appeared wholly, half, or peak-only visible—like seeing only a person's topknot through a tent.

    Gazing at the absolute peak, layered ridges piled beyond comprehension—yesterday's path vanished completely. A white flag beside the Holy Mother Temple pointed southward—the painting monk signaling us. We admired the northern and southern cliffs, awaiting the moon. The eastern sky remained obscure and bitter cold prevented lingering. We burned pine logs to heat the building before retiring. Midnight brought brilliant stars and moon.

    At dawn on the third day, the sun rose resplendent with glowing colors. My companions thought my exhaustion so complete I could never climb again. But I reflected: "Days of rain, then sudden clearing—heaven has given me much. Should I not grasp this moment at arm's length? The rigidity in my chest these many years—will it never dissolve?" We hastened breakfast, tucked up our robes, and climbed, passing through stone gates where everything wore ice.

    Entering the Holy Mother Temple again, I made renewed offering: "Today heaven and earth shine clear. Mountains and streams lie open. This surely flows from divine grace. My gratitude knows no bounds." Then with Geuk-gi and Haegong, I ascended the northern rampart. Tae-heo had already reached the wooden platform—higher than even flying cranes could soar.

    With no clouds anywhere, only vast and boundless space, I said: "To gaze far without grasping its essence differs not from a woodcutter's vision. Shall we not first observe north, then east, then south, then west, proceeding from near to far?" Haegong skillfully pointed out features.

    The mountain rushes northward to Namwon, rises as Prajna Peak, extends eastward nearly two hundred miles, rises higher still, arcs northward, and ends. Countless subsidiary peaks and ravines compete in prominence and cascade in torrents—no calculator could count them all. What appeared as city walls dragged upward, mingled blue-yellow light with white rainbows crossing—was this Hamyang's fortress and waters? Blue spirals rising, spreading horizontally, standing vertically—were these South Sea and Geoje's islands? Mountain Shade, Crimson Ravine, Cloud Peak, Gurae, and Hadong counties hid within the folds, invisible. Mountains nearby to the north: Yellow Stone, Deerpeek near Hamyang; Virtue Mountain, Eagle Rock far off. Northwest mountains included Gaya, Rooster Dragon from various regions. To the east: Royal Mountain near Mountain Shade; Indigo Peak nearby. South sea direction showed Supine Dragon from Sacheon and Mist waters of various names. Western mountains included Myriad Equal Peak from various provinces.

    Some peaks resembled earthen mounds, some dragons and tigers, some treasure vessels, some sword blades. Only Palsung Peak to the east and Myriad Equal to the west rose more prominently than others. Beyond Rooster Ridge northward, green mist filled the sky. Below the island of Tsushima southward, mirage-mist touched the heavens. Our vision exhausted, we could distinguish no further. I had Geuk-gi record what we could identify.

    We gazed at each other in joy: "Since ancient times others have climbed this peak. But has any equaled today's perfection?" We descended the rampart, sat on stone steps, and drank several cups—the sun already at midday. Seeing Lingxhen's High Terrace still distant, we hurried through the stone gates and descended.

    We climbed Middle Peak—also an earth mountain. Those from Eomcheon ascending made the north's second peak the central mountain; those from Horse Stream made Steamer Peak first and this second. Hence its name. From here the ridge path continued; a dozen extraordinary peaks lined the way, all climbable for views, equal to the highest peak yet unnamed.

    Geuk-gi said: "How do we add names without evidence?"

    I said: "So be it."

    The forest held abundant horse-price wood fit for staffs. We had attendants select smooth, straight pieces. Soon a full bundle gathered. Beyond Steamer Peak lay Submerged Ravine—a maple tree barred the path, shaped like a door frame. Passing through, no one needed to crouch. The ravine lay on the ridge, level and expansive, five or six miles across with dense groves and circling springs—tillable ground providing sustenance. We saw several reed shelters within brushwood fences and earthen hearths—the eagle-catching camps.

    From Younglang Pass to here, I'd seen eagle-catching apparatus scattered across the landscape uncountably. Though still early autumn with no capturing occurring, I reflected: Eagles fly through clouds—how do they know of apparatus on these steep heights? Seeing bait, they greedily seize it, caught in nets and control cords. Surely this teaches a lesson. Yet for mere gifts of one or two pairs, officials hunt profit from entertainment, sending frost-clad, meager folk to endure wind and snow on thousand-foot peaks day and night. Those with compassion cannot bear it.

    That evening we reached Singing Buddha Terrace—high, perilous, isolated. Below lay bottomless void; above grew no vegetation save a few azaleas and wild goat droppings. Gazing upon Bean Ravine, Yeosu Stream, and Seomjin's junction, mountains and sea overlapped in extraordinary beauty. Haegong pointed where ravines converged: "New Rising Temple Ravine. There the general Li Geukyun fought bandit Zhang Younggi. Though Younggi clung to dangerous terrain, Li's cunning and valor could not contain his assault—only the Jianghung commander finally eliminated him. Shameful indeed."

    He pointed northward: "Blue Crane Temple Ravine—surely this is what ancient peoples called the realm of immortals? It lies not distant from human lands, yet Limei couldn't find it. Perhaps lovers of such tales built the temple and named it thus."

    He indicated eastward: "Twin Stream Temple Ravine. Choi Goweun once wandered here, leaving inscriptions in stone. Goweun was a spirited man—self-assured, he met chaotic times ill-treated in both China and the East. So he abandoned society for secluded mountain streams. Everywhere he traveled, posterity calls him immortal—rightfully so."

    We lodged at Lingxhen Temple. Only one monk remained. On the northern cliff stood a Kasyapa stone image. In Great Ancestor Sejong's time, court emissaries regularly made offerings. The statue bore a crack, also struck away by pirates. Its right shoulder bore scars—supposedly from cosmic fire. "Add more burning and Maitreya's age arrives," they said.

    But stone naturally bears such marks; monks deceived ignorant folk with wild tales, making them pour out money and cloth seeking future reward. Truly abhorrent! North of the Kasyapa shrine stood two cliffs—the so-called High Terrace. One had a flat base tapering to a peak, topped with a stone barely a foot wide. Monks claimed those who climb there and worship gain enlightenment. Our attendants Okgun and Yeomjeong scrambled up and bowed. I saw them from below, hastily sent someone to stop them. These blockheads barely distinguished grain and beans, yet dared wager their lives! The monks' deception is evident even here.

    In the temple hall hung a Mengshan painting with verses: "The Thadah ranked first—this is the shaking off. Externally already distant from dust; internally already freed from defilements. Gaining the way came before; entering extinction came after. Snowy robes on Rooster Mountain—ten thousand autumns unrotted." Beside it a seal read: "Qingzhi's small seal script"—surely among Fexyeah Hall's three marvels. Below the eastern steps flowed Spirit Creek; below western steps, Jade Spring with flavor superior to Middle Spring and Huishan. West of the spring stood collapsed ruins—the ancient Lingxhen Temple. At the northwest's broken peak, a small pagoda of fine stone remains—also toppled by pirates, later reassembled with iron reinforcement, yet missing several layers.

    On the fifth day, opening the doors early, I saw the Seomjin tide swelling, but gazing longer realized it was merely mist. After breakfast, we rested atop a ridge northwest of the temple. Gazing toward Prajna Peak, some sixty miles distant, my feet were bruised and my strength exhausted—though I longed to climb, I could not force myself. We descended directly, the path increasingly treacherous, grasping tree roots and stone corners through dozens of miles of this terrain. Facing east toward Heaven King Peak, it seemed at arm's length. Some bamboo retained seeds, though people had gathered them; great pines—perhaps ten arm-spans girth—were rare elsewhere.

    Below the steep approach where two ravines merged, the waters roared and thundered while a hundred-foot clear pool held fish that swam in crowds. Our four gathered water to rinse teeth and, dragging staffs along the cliff side, proceeded most pleasantly. At the ravine's mouth stood a wild temple where our horse attendant waited. We changed clothes, mounted, and reached Silzack Village. Several elders came to greet us on the road, bowing: "We rejoice the magistrate returned unharmed from his wandering."

    I was glad my people did not blame me for leisure neglecting duty. Haegong went to Junjasal, Beopjong to Myojeongsae, while Tae-heo, Geuk-gi, and Baek-won visited Dragon Play Pool. I crossed Turtle Pass and returned directly to the magistrate's residence.

    Our outing lasted merely five days, yet my chest expanded and my spirit cleared. Even my wife and servants noticed I seemed transformed. Alas, should Mount Duryu possess such sublime grandeur, were it in the Central Land, it would surely precede Sung and Tai, the celestial sealing sites, inscribed in gold and jade scrolls for heavenly presentation. Failing that, it would compare with Wuyi and Hengshan, drawing Confucian scholars like Han Changfei and Zhu Heuiam and immortal adepts like Sun Xingong and Lü Dongbin—their robes mingling as they wandered these slopes.

    Yet today it serves merely as refuge for common rogues and unregistered people studying Buddhism. Though we finally attained one ascent, barely satisfying our long desire, official constraints prevent exploring Blue Crane's secrets, traversing Five Terraces' mysteries. Is this the mountain's misfortune or ours? Yet reading Du Fu's verse—"The square-foot encompasses three Han"—my soul still soars.
  footnotes:
    - The Book of Caring for Parents (Shou Chin Shu) was a popular guide for filial conduct and included recommendations for wholesome activities like mountain travel.
    - The Ghost Festival (Yulanpen) was observed on the 15th day of the 7th lunar month and marked the conclusion of the three-month Buddhist summer retreat.
    - Heaven King Peak is the highest point of Mount Duryu and was believed to be a sacred site. The Holy Mother Temple housed both Buddhist and indigenous Korean religious elements.
    - The reference to Japanese pirates (倭寇) alludes to the Wokou raids that plagued the Korean peninsula during the Joseon period.
    - The names of countless peaks and distant mountains visible from the summit demonstrate the geographic significance of Mount Duryu as a commanding vantage point in the Korean landscape.
    - Du Fu's phrase about 'the square-foot encompassing three Han' is a poetic reference to the ability of one supreme location to contain the essence of vast territories.
